out 1311":"about 1311","1307":"1307","1317":"1317","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Barry, Glamorgan, Wales":"Barry, Glamorgan, Wales","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Anatole, Emile, Pierre, Alphonse, Andre, Cecile, Henri, Herve, Jacques, Marcel, Regean, Yves.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a gateway or barrier, or in a house encircled by a fence, from Old French <i>barre</i> ‘bar, obstruction’ (of obscure origin, possibly akin to the Celtic element <i>barr</i> ‘height’); or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, e.g. Barre-en-Ouche in Eure or Barre-de-Semilly in Manche. Compare   Labarre  .","French: probably also a habitational name from Barre in Lozère, named with the Celtic element <i>barr</i> ‘height’."],"variants":[{"name":"Labarre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Alain, Andre, Armand, Aurore, Fernande, Gilles, Herve, Laure, Michel, Urbain.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a gateway or barrier, or in a house encircled by a fence, from Old French <i>barre</i> ‘bar, obstruction’ (see   Barre   1), with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, e.g. Barre-en-Ouche in Eure or Barre-de-Semilly in Manche. Compare   Labar  ,   Labare  ,   Labarr  ,   Labor  ,   Labore  ,   Lebar  , and   Lebarre  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Jacques Genest or Genet <i>dit</i> Labarre from France (see   Genest  )."]},{"name":"Baray","meanings":["Hispanic (Mexico): unexplained.","In some cases possibly also French: variant of <b>Barray</b>, itself a variant of <b>Barrey</b>, a derivative of   Barre   1. In France, it is found mainly in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Barrere","meanings":["French (<b>Barrère</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate or barrier, or a metonymic occupational name for a gatekeeper, from a derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1); or a habitational name from (La) Barrère, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France.","English: variant of <b>Barrer</b>, for someone who lived by a town or castle gate, from Middle English <i>barre</i> ‘barrier, gateway’. Compare above and   Barr   4."]},{"name":"Barriere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Gaston, Monique, Philippe.","French (<b>Barrière</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate or barrier, or a metonymic occupational name for a gatekeeper, from a derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1); or a habitational name from (La) Barrière, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Gates  ."]},{"name":"Barreau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Fresnel, Gabrielle, Jean-Louis, Jean-Marie, Jeanty, Michel, Michelene, Pierre.","French:","derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1), hence a nickname for a fence keeper or a topographic name for someone who lived in a house encircled by a fence."]},{"name":"Barrier","meanings":["French: occupational name for a gatekeeper, from Old French <i>barier</i>, an agent derivative of <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1).","Altered form of French   Barriere  .","Altered form of German   Berger  ."]},{"name":"Barra","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Marina, Antonio, Augusto, Biagio, Carlo, Domenic, Flavio, Gennaro, Lorenzo, Luciano, Rocco, Salvatore.  Spanish Jorge, Carlos, Diego, Enrique, Jaime, Juan, Manuel.","Italian (southern), Spanish, and Portuguese: topographic name from <i>barra</i> ‘bar, rod’ (in the sense of ‘barrier, sandbank’), or a habitational name from any of the places called with this word.","French (southern): dialect variant of   Barre   1."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"la","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Olaf  , also widely used in southwest Sweden."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Thomas de la Barre was born in 1281, in Barry, Glamorgan, Wales. She married Thomas de la Barre about 1302, in Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 7 sons."},"et":{"1281–":"1281–Surnud","1279–1343":"1279–1343","1305–1388":"1305–1388","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1307–Male":"1307–Surnud","1311–Male":"1311–Surnud","1313–Male":"1313–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1317–Male":"1317–Surnud","1281–Female":"1281–Surnud","1281":"1281","Abt 1305":"umbes 1305","1305":"1305","1315":"1315","about 1307":"umbes 1307","1313":"1313","about 1305":"umbes 1305","1279":"1279","about 1317":"umbes 1317","1311":"1311","1388":"1388","1343":"1343","about 1315":"umbes 1315","about 1302":"umbes 1302","about 1313":"umbes 1313","about 1311":"umbes 1311","1307":"1307","1317":"1317","Paston, Norfolk, Eng